# Mule Flow Generation & Modification

The agent hand-writes Mule XML in this project (no MCP). Follow these patterns precisely — schema errors and runtime crashes mostly come from violating one of the rules below.

## Naming

- Flows: `<feature>-<verb>-flow` (e.g. `customers-get-flow`, `orders-create-flow`)
- Sub-flows: `<feature>-<step>-sub-flow` (e.g. `orders-validate-sub-flow`)
- Every processor MUST have `doc:name="<descriptive name>"`

## Comments — Use `doc:name`, Not `<!-- -->` Inside `<flow>`

The agent MUST NOT place `<!-- … -->` comments **inside** a `<flow>…</flow>` body, an `<error-handler>…</error-handler>` body, or a `<sub-flow>…</sub-flow>` body. Every step's purpose is conveyed via the `doc:name="…"` attribute on the processor itself — that's what ACB renders in the visual flow designer, what shows up in logs, and what MUnit references in failure output. An inline `<!-- ── Step N: do the thing ─── -->` above a processor that already has `doc:name="Do the thing"` is pure duplication and clutter.

```xml
<!-- WRONG — narrative comment duplicating doc:name -->
<flow name="customers-create-flow">
  <!-- ── Step 1: Read the bundled JSON file ─────────────── -->
  <ee:transform doc:name="Read source customers">
    ...
  </ee:transform>

  <!-- ── Step 2: Build the SF Account collection ─────────── -->
  <ee:transform doc:name="Build SF Account collection">
    ...
  </ee:transform>
</flow>
```

```xml
<!-- RIGHT — same flow, no inline comments; doc:name carries the story -->
<flow name="customers-create-flow">
  <ee:transform doc:name="Read source customers">
    ...
  </ee:transform>

  <ee:transform doc:name="Build SF Account collection">
    ...
  </ee:transform>
</flow>
```

### Where comments ARE allowed

- **File-level header above `<mule>` or directly under `<mule>` before the first `<flow>`** — design notes, ADR references, "this file owns endpoints X / Y / Z", or a short rationale for an unusual pattern. Keep these terse: 2–6 lines is plenty. If the rationale is long enough to need paragraphs, put it in `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` § Decisions Log instead and reference the decision date here.
- **Inside DataWeave bodies** — DW has its own comment syntax (`// line`, `/* block */`); use those when a transform really needs explaining. They sit inside the `<![CDATA[…]]>` and never duplicate `doc:name`.
- **Inside a configuration element** that explains a non-obvious attribute choice (rare). Example: explaining why a particular `pollingFrequency` was picked.

### Why this rule exists

1. **`doc:name` is the only label that survives** — it's what ACB's visual designer shows, what Mule writes to logs (`flow:CustomersCreate.transform("Build SF Account collection")`), and what MUnit references in test failure output. Inline `<!-- -->` comments are invisible everywhere except the raw XML.
2. **Comment drift** — narrative comments rot the moment a flow is reordered, a processor is renamed, or a step is removed. `doc:name` rots too if you don't update it, but at least the rot is visible in the visual designer and in logs.
3. **Reading time** — a clean `<flow>` body with descriptive `doc:name` attributes reads like a numbered table of contents. The same flow with bracketed step comments reads like a stream-of-consciousness essay. The agent is supposed to be writing maintainable XML, not annotating its own thought process.

### How to convey "intent" without an inline comment

- **Step purpose** → put it in `doc:name="Pre-compute upsert failure flag and error details"` (verb + object, ~5–8 words)
- **Why this step exists at all** → either it's obvious from `doc:name`, or it's an architectural decision that belongs in `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` § Decisions Log, NOT in flow XML
- **A non-obvious DW expression inside an `<ee:transform>`** → use a DW comment INSIDE the `<![CDATA[…]]>` block: `// reduce with initial {} handles empty payload`
- **A workaround for a known runtime bug** → file-level header comment with a one-line link/reference (e.g. "Lambdas pre-computed in <ee:transform> to avoid Mule 4.11 AlertingSupport NPE — see mule-flow-generation.mdc § Choice Predicates"). Keep it at the top of the file, not buried mid-flow.

### Pre-deploy grep — add to your check list

```powershell
# Detects an inline <!-- ... --> comment that lives inside a <flow>, <sub-flow>,
# or <error-handler> body (multiline mode required because comments span lines).
Select-String -Path 'src/main/mule/*.xml' -Pattern '(?s)<(?:flow|sub-flow|error-handler)\b[^>]*>.*?<!--.*?-->.*?</(?:flow|sub-flow|error-handler)>'
```

Any non-empty result means an inline comment slipped past — strip it before declaring the work done.

## Required XML Root

Every flow file MUST declare `xmlns:doc` — missing it causes the build to fail with `The prefix "doc" for attribute "doc:name" is not bound`.

```xml
<mule xmlns="http://www.mulesoft.org/schema/mule/core"
      xmlns:doc="http://www.mulesoft.org/schema/mule/documentation"
      xmlns:http="http://www.mulesoft.org/schema/mule/http"
      xmlns:ee="http://www.mulesoft.org/schema/mule/ee/core"
      xsi:schemaLocation="...">
  <!-- flows go here -->
</mule>
```

## HTTP Listener — Response Configuration

Always configure BOTH success and error responses so error status codes propagate correctly:

```xml
<http:listener config-ref="HTTP_Listener_config" path="/api/v1/customers" allowedMethods="POST" doc:name="POST /customers">
  <http:response statusCode="201">
    <http:headers>#[output application/java --- { "Content-Type": "application/json" }]</http:headers>
  </http:response>
  <http:error-response statusCode="#[vars.httpStatus default 500]">
    <http:body>#[output application/json --- { code: vars.errorCode default "INTERNAL_ERROR", message: vars.errorMessage default error.description }]</http:body>
    <http:headers>#[output application/java --- { "Content-Type": "application/json" }]</http:headers>
  </http:error-response>
</http:listener>
```

**Gotcha**: `method=` is NOT a valid attribute on `<http:listener>`. Use `allowedMethods="GET"` (comma-separated for multiple, e.g. `"GET,POST"`).

## Error Handling — MANDATORY

Every flow must have an `<error-handler>` with:

- Specific `<on-error-propagate>` blocks for each known error type (e.g. `APP:BAD_REQUEST`, `APP:NOT_FOUND`)
- A catch-all `<on-error-propagate type="ANY">` at the end

Use `on-error-propagate` (NOT `on-error-continue`) in **outer** flow handlers so `<http:error-response>` fires with the correct status code.

Use `on-error-continue` ONLY inside `<try>` blocks for localized handling that re-raises a new error type.

```xml
<error-handler>
  <on-error-propagate type="APP:BAD_REQUEST" doc:name="Bad Request 400">
    <ee:transform>
      <ee:variables>
        <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus">400</ee:set-variable>
        <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">"BAD_REQUEST"</ee:set-variable>
        <ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage">error.description</ee:set-variable>
      </ee:variables>
    </ee:transform>
  </on-error-propagate>
  <on-error-propagate type="APP:NOT_FOUND" doc:name="Not Found 404">
    <ee:transform>
      <ee:variables>
        <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus">404</ee:set-variable>
        <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">"NOT_FOUND"</ee:set-variable>
      </ee:variables>
    </ee:transform>
  </on-error-propagate>
  <on-error-propagate type="ANY" doc:name="Internal Error 500">
    <ee:transform>
      <ee:variables>
        <ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus">500</ee:set-variable>
        <ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode">"INTERNAL_ERROR"</ee:set-variable>
      </ee:variables>
    </ee:transform>
  </on-error-propagate>
</error-handler>
```

## User-Friendly Error Responses — MANDATORY

API responses (success AND error) must be CLEAN, ACTIONABLE JSON. The agent MUST NEVER return:

- Raw connector payloads (e.g. `BatchOperationResult`, JDBC `ResultSet`, HTTP request `MultiMap`)
- Internal Java toString output (`org.mule.runtime.api.metadata.TypedValue@abc123`)
- Stack traces, hex hashes, or debug dumps
- Generic fallbacks like `"Unexpected response: { … huge raw json … }"`
- `error.description` directly when the underlying connector wraps a meaningful business error

### Standard error envelope (every flow, every connector)

```json
{ "code": "INVALID_FIELD", "message": "BillingCountry: invalid country code 'XYZ' (fields: BillingCountry)" }
```

That is two fields. `code` is a stable, screaming-snake-case enum the caller can branch on. `message` is human-readable, names the offending field/value when relevant, and is safe to show in a UI.

### Standard success envelope

For creates: `{ "id": "<resource-id>", "status": "created" }`
For updates: `{ "id": "<resource-id>", "status": "updated" }`
For deletes: `{ "id": "<resource-id>", "status": "deleted" }`
For queries: the actual data, NOT a wrapper like `{ "items": [...], "successful": true }` (that's the connector's shape, not the API's).

### Pattern — capture connector errors in the SUB-FLOW, map to HTTP in the OUTER handler

1. **Sub-flow** (where the connector lives): walk the connector response, set `vars.<name>ErrorCode` + `vars.<name>ErrorMessage`, then `<raise-error type="APP:<CONNECTOR>_ERROR" description="...">`.
2. **Outer flow's `<error-handler>`**: catch `APP:<CONNECTOR>_ERROR`, set `vars.errorCode` / `vars.errorMessage` from the captured vars (NOT from `error.description` directly), and compute `vars.httpStatus` based on the connector's status code.
3. **`<http:error-response>`**: always uses `vars.httpStatus` / `vars.errorCode` / `vars.errorMessage`.

`vars.*` set before `<raise-error>` survive into the error handler — exploit this so the outer handler stays small and connector-agnostic.

### Connector-specific guidance

- Salesforce: `mule-salesforce.mdc` §7 (read `payload.items[0]`, NEVER `payload[0]`; map SF `statusCode` → HTTP)
- Database: `mule-database.mdc` (capture `DB:CONNECTIVITY`, `DB:BAD_SQL_SYNTAX`, `DB:QUERY_EXECUTION` separately)
- HTTP outbound: capture `HTTP:CONNECTIVITY`, `HTTP:CLIENT_ERROR_*`, `HTTP:SERVER_ERROR_*` separately and surface upstream `code` + `message` from the response body when the upstream is JSON

### Wrong vs Right (Salesforce example)

WRONG (what the user sees today if rules are violated):
```json
{ "code": "SALESFORCE_REJECTED", "message": "Unexpected SF response (no errors[] populated): {\n  \"id\": null, \"items\": [{ \"payload\": {...}}], \"successful\": true\n}" }
```

RIGHT:
```json
{ "code": "INVALID_FIELD", "message": "BillingCountry: invalid country code 'XYZ' (fields: BillingCountry)" }
```

If you find yourself writing `"Unexpected … : " ++ write(payload, "application/json")` in a user-facing message, STOP. That's a sign the connector response shape isn't being read correctly — fix the parser instead, and only log the raw payload (at WARN/DEBUG), never return it.

## Validation Pattern (Inside `<try>`)

```xml
<try>
  <flow-ref name="customers-validate-sub-flow"/>
  <error-handler>
    <on-error-continue type="OS:KEY_NOT_FOUND">
      <raise-error type="APP:NOT_FOUND" description="Customer not found"/>
    </on-error-continue>
  </error-handler>
</try>
```

## Configs — Reuse, Don't Duplicate

- HTTP listener config: shared `HTTP_Listener_config` from `global-configs.xml`
- HTTP request (outbound): named config in `global-configs.xml` with base URI from `config.yaml`
- Database / Salesforce / Object Store configs: all in `global-configs.xml` — see the dedicated rules
- Object Store: define `<os:object-store>` in the flow file using `persistent="false"` for dev/test

## DataWeave in Flows

- Inline DWL for simple transforms (< 5 lines)
- External `.dwl` in `src/main/resources/dwl/` for anything larger; reference via `<ee:set-payload resource="dwl/customer-mapping.dwl"/>`
- See `mule-dataweave.mdc` for full DWL rules

## Choice Predicates — Keep Them Trivial (Mule 4.11.x AlertingSupport NPE)

Mule 4.11.x has a runtime defect where a `<choice>`/`<when>` expression that performs non-trivial DataWeave evaluation can throw:

```
NullPointerException: Cannot invoke "org.mule.runtime.api.alert.AlertingSupport.triggerAlert(String, Object)"
because the return value of "java.util.Map.get(Object)" is null
```

surfaced as error type `MULE:UNKNOWN`. The runtime tries to fire an internal alert during expression evaluation but the alerts map for that scope isn't populated, so the NPE *masks* the real underlying issue and the error bubbles up to your `ANY` handler as a generic 500 `INTERNAL_ERROR`. Worse: anything the flow already DML'd before the failing `<choice>` (Account upsert, DB insert, ObjectStore write) **stays committed** — Mule does not auto-rollback — so you end up with partial state in the downstream system and no clear error message about what went wrong.

This bug is hard to debug because the failure point in the stack trace is the `<choice>` itself, not the line of DataWeave that broke. The rule below avoids the bug entirely AND makes future debugging easier.

### Forbidden — complex predicate inside `<when>`

Anything in this list inside a `<when expression="#[...]">` is a deploy-blocker:

- Lambda parameters: `((x) -> ...)` or `((x, i) -> ...)`
- Higher-order ops: `map`, `filter`, `some`, `every`, `find`, `flatMap`, `reduce`, `groupBy`, `joinBy`
- String functions: `upper`, `lower`, `trim`, `replace`, `substring`, `match`
- Type coercion: `as String`, `as Number`, `as Boolean`, `as Object`, `as Date`
- Null-safe chains beyond a single `default`: `(x.y default {}).z default ""`
- Block expressions: `do { ... }`
- Module function calls: `dw::core::strings::*`, `dw::Crypto::*`, etc.

```xml
<!-- WRONG — complex lambda inside <when>, triggers Mule 4.11 AlertingSupport NPE -->
<choice doc:name="Has any buyer">
  <when expression="#[vars.originalAccounts some ((r) -> (r.IsBuyer == true) or (upper((r.IsBuyer as String default '')) == 'TRUE'))]">
    ...
  </when>
</choice>
```

### Required — pre-compute in `<ee:transform>`, predicate is just `sizeOf`/comparison

Push the work into a preceding `<ee:transform>` that lands the answer in a `vars.*` variable. The `<choice>` predicate then becomes trivial.

```xml
<ee:transform doc:name="Pre-compute buyer rows">
  <ee:variables>
    <ee:set-variable variableName="buyerRows"><![CDATA[%dw 2.0
output application/java
---
vars.originalAccounts filter ((r) ->
  (r.IsBuyer == true) or (upper(((r.IsBuyer default "") as String)) == "TRUE")
)]]></ee:set-variable>
  </ee:variables>
</ee:transform>

<choice doc:name="Has any buyer">
  <when expression="#[sizeOf(vars.buyerRows default []) > 0]">
    ...
  </when>
  <otherwise>...</otherwise>
</choice>
```

### The whitelist — what `<when>` expressions ARE allowed

`<when expression="#[...]">` may ONLY contain:

- `sizeOf(vars.X default [])` style length checks
- Boolean combinators: `and`, `or`, `not`
- Comparisons: `==`, `!=`, `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=`
- Direct variable / payload / attribute access: `vars.X`, `payload.field`, `attributes.headers.Foo`
- A single literal `default` to handle null: `vars.X default 0`
- Built-in single-value introspection used as filters: `payload is Array`, `payload is Object`, `payload is String`

Anything outside this whitelist → move it to an `<ee:transform>` first. No exceptions, even if the expression "looks simple" to a human — the bug fires on shape, not complexity score.

### Why this rule also improves debuggability

| If the bug is in… | …error type the handler sees | …and the location | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `<when expression="#[<complex>]">` (forbidden) | `MULE:UNKNOWN` (NPE) | The `<choice>` element — opaque | Real cause is masked; can leave partial Salesforce/DB state |
| `<ee:transform>` (required) | `MULE:EXPRESSION` (clean DW error with line/column) | The transform — pinpoints the broken expression | Catchable as a real error type; map to 400 `BAD_INPUT` |

### Pre-deploy grep — add to your check list

```powershell
# Detects lambda parameters or higher-order ops inside a <when expression="#[...]">
Select-String -Path 'src/main/mule/*.xml' `
  -Pattern '<when\s+expression="#\[[^"]*(\)\s*->|\bsome\b|\bevery\b|\bmap\s*\(|\bfilter\s*\(|\bupper\s*\(|\blower\s*\(|\sas\s+(String|Number|Boolean|Object|Date))'
```

Any match is a deploy-blocker. Refactor the predicate into a preceding `<ee:transform>` before continuing.

## Common Gotchas

- **CDATA — only one valid close sequence** — In XML, a CDATA section **must** end with exactly **`]]>`** (two `]` characters, then `>`). Nothing else may appear between your DataWeave text and that terminator except the characters that are **part of the expression**.

- **Deploy failure signature** — If you see `Invalid input ']', expected ~, Function Call or selectors` pointing at an `<ee:set-variable>` or `<http:body>` line, you almost certainly have **an extra `]`** before `]]>` (often looks like `]]]>` at end of file or `"]]]>` after a quoted string).

- **WRONG — extra `]` before CDATA end** (breaks deploy; stray `]` is parsed as DataWeave):

```xml
<ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode"><![CDATA["INTERNAL_ERROR"]]]></ee:set-variable>
```

  Here the author typed **`]]]>`** (three `]` before `>`). XML closes CDATA at the **first** valid `]]>`, leaving malformed content / a lone `]` — runtime parses garbage as DW.

- **RIGHT — exactly `]]>` after the expression**:

```xml
<ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode"><![CDATA["INTERNAL_ERROR"]]></ee:set-variable>
```

- **Object literal at end of CDATA** — Expression ends with `}`; CDATA ends with **`]]>`** immediately after that brace (no extra `]`):

```xml
<![CDATA[#[output application/json --- { code: "X" }]]>
```

  Here **`}]]>`** means: `}` ends the DataWeave object, then **`]]>`** closes CDATA — exactly **two** `]` characters before `>`. **Never** use **`}]]]>`** (that inserts an extra `]` and can reproduce the same deploy error).

- **NEVER put `value="..."` on `<ee:set-variable>` (EE core)** — The Mule Maven plugin validates flow XML against the EE schema. **`value` is not a valid attribute** on `<ee:set-variable>`. You get:

  `cvc-complex-type.3.2.2: Attribute 'value' is not allowed to appear in element 'ee:set-variable'.`

  Put literals and expressions in the **element body** instead:

```xml
<ee:set-variable variableName="httpStatus" doc:name="httpStatus">503</ee:set-variable>
<ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode" doc:name="errorCode">#["INTERNAL_ERROR"]</ee:set-variable>
<ee:set-variable variableName="errorMessage" doc:name="errorMessage">#[error.description]</ee:set-variable>
```

  (Core Mule `<set-variable>` may allow `value=` in other contexts; this project uses **`xmlns:ee`** transforms — follow body content only.)

- **Prefer skipping CDATA for short constants** — avoids `]]>` typos; still use **body**, not `value=`:

```xml
<ee:set-variable variableName="errorCode" doc:name="errorCode">#["INTERNAL_ERROR"]</ee:set-variable>
```

- **HTTP listener bodies** — If you wrap `#[output ... --- { ... }]` in CDATA, the sequence after the closing `}` is **`]]>`** only, e.g. `... }]]>` inside `<![CDATA[ ... ]]>` (see `}]]>` above — still only two `]` before `>`).
- `var input = payload` is INVALID in DW header — never assign `payload` to a variable
- `error()` is NOT a standard DW function — use `<choice>` + `<raise-error>` for validation
- Object Store `<os:store>` saves whatever you give it. If you used `output application/json` before storing, you stored a **JSON string**. Use `output application/java` BEFORE store, then a separate `output application/json` AFTER for the HTTP response.
- Object Store `retrieve-all` returns a Java Map of keys → values; use `valuesOf(payload)` to get an array
- Object Store `retrieve` returns the object directly — no `read()` needed
- `flow-ref` target name must match the `<flow name="...">` exactly (case-sensitive)

## Self-Test Gate — MANDATORY before declaring flow / DW work done

The agent MUST NOT report a flow change as "done" or recommend the user run / smoke-test until ALL of the steps below pass. Skipping a step and shipping the change to the user is a workflow regression — the user pays for the deploy-fail loop in 90-second increments.

### Required gates, in order

1. **Lint** — run `ReadLints` on every edited XML / DW file. Treat any `[ERROR]` as a deploy-blocker. Fix before continuing. (Warnings are OK to leave if they are pre-existing or known type-inference noise.)

2. **Mule reachable check** — confirm the runtime is up by checking `Get-NetTCPConnection -LocalPort 8081 -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` returns a connection (or just attempting `Invoke-WebRequest http://localhost:8081/api/v1/products -TimeoutSec 5 -SkipHttpErrorCheck`). If not running, ask the user to start it via task `Mule: Run (Cursor)` BEFORE proceeding to step 3 — don't assume it's up.

3. **Smoke test** — run `scripts/smoke-test.ps1` (or task `Mule: Smoke test`). The script:
   - Hits every endpoint in `API.md`.
   - Asserts on HTTP status, response shape, AND known sample values from the bundled fixtures.
   - Exits 0 on full pass, 1 on any failure with a per-case PASS/FAIL summary.

   The agent MUST report the script's exit code and the summary line in the response. If exit code is non-zero, fix the issue and re-run — don't hand a failing change back to the user.

4. **Update fixtures if surface changed** — if the change added/removed an endpoint, changed a field name, changed a status code, or changed an error code, the agent MUST update `scripts/smoke-test.ps1` in the SAME response so the new gate is meaningful. A green smoke test on stale assertions is worse than a red one.

### Why smoke might still miss a bug (agent MUST avoid this)

1. **Smoke was never run** after the change — the Self-Test Gate requires running `scripts/smoke-test.ps1` and reporting exit code; skipping this is a regression.
2. **Stale deployment** — the user (or agent) ran smoke against an **old** jar still in the runtime `apps/` folder while the IDE has newer XML. Always rebuild (`mvn package`) and redeploy / restart so the running app matches the branch.
3. **Wrong gate** — `mvn package` alone does **not** execute `readUrl`, `<choice>` expressions, or connector calls; it only validates XML schema and packaging. Runtime-only failures require step 3 (smoke) or manual `Invoke-RestMethod`.

Before marking DW + HTTP work done, the agent SHOULD **`grep` `src/main/mule` for `readUrl` / `resource://`** and fix any `resource://` per `mule-dataweave.mdc`.

### What the smoke test catches that the linter cannot

- `readUrl` MIME-type bugs (parsed fine, fails at runtime — see `mule-dataweave.mdc`)
- **`readUrl` URL scheme bugs** (e.g. `resource://` instead of `classpath://`) — XML/DW still **parses and packages**; only a **live HTTP hit** after deploy fails. Maven does not evaluate DataWeave.
- Wrong status codes (200 returned where 404 expected, etc.)
- Wrong error envelope shape (`code` field missing, `message` empty)
- Wrong field names in the response (e.g. `Price` vs `price`)
- Wrong field types (e.g. a numeric field returned as a quoted string `"193.52"` instead of a JSON number)
- Stale `vars` references that compile but resolve to null at runtime
- Connector mocks that succeed in MUnit but fail against the real connector

The lint gate catches **parse-time** bugs. The smoke gate catches **runtime** bugs. Both classes are in scope; both gates are required.

### Scheduled jobs (`JOBS.md` + `mule-scheduler-jobs.mdc`)

HTTP smoke tests cannot trigger `<scheduler>`. When adding or changing **scheduled** flows:

1. Document the job in **`JOBS.md`** (not `API.md`) — see **`mule-scheduler-jobs.mdc`**.
2. Implement **business logic in a `<sub-flow>`** and expose a **manual `<http:listener>`** flow that **`flow-ref`s the same sub-flow** for local verification.
3. Add **one smoke-test case per manual-trigger path** (method, path, expected status + minimal JSON shape) — documented in `JOBS.md` § Manual test hook.
4. The agent **MUST** run `scripts/smoke-test.ps1` after editing smoke cases and report exit code.

Do **not** require API-style `vars.httpStatus` mapping for scheduler flows; the manual HTTP trigger may still return a simple 200 JSON envelope for smoke assertions.

### When the gate is allowed to be skipped

Only when:
- The change is purely documentation (`API.md`, `JOBS.md`, `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md`, `*.mdc` rule files, README).
- The change is purely to a `.dwl` test-fixture file under `src/test/resources/` that no flow loads.
- The change is to `pom.xml` or `mule-artifact.json` AND no XML/DW was touched (in which case run `mvn validate` instead).

In every other case, the gate runs.

## After Editing

- Run `MuleSoft: Validate Project` in ACB to catch schema issues early
- Reload Window if completion / hover info goes stale
